  <h2>Nunavut Garden Timing Notes</h2>

  <p>
    Gardening in Nunavut operates at the edge of what’s climatically possible for food production.
    Extremely short frost-free windows, cool summer temperatures, and rapid seasonal shifts mean
    crop selection and protection strategy matter more than exact planting dates.
  </p>

  <h3>1) The calendar season is very short</h3>
  <p>
    Frost can occur in any month in some locations. Even during peak summer, cool overnight lows
    can slow crop development. That makes realistic maturity expectations essential.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If you’re planning crops in a tight window, this guide on
    <a href="/guides/what-crops-grow-in-short-growing-seasons/">
      crops that grow well in short seasons
    </a>
    provides a practical starting point.
  </p>

  <h3>2) Daylight is abundant — heat is limited</h3>
  <p>
    Long summer daylight hours promote leafy growth, but limited total heat accumulation
    restricts long-season fruiting crops. Greens, root vegetables, and fast brassicas are
    generally more reliable than tomatoes, peppers, or winter squash.
  </p>

  <h3>3) Protection is often necessary</h3>
  <p>
    Low tunnels, cold frames, and sheltered raised beds can make the difference between
    marginal and successful harvests. Protection is less about luxury and more about
    creating a workable microclimate.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If you’re considering season extension, this explains the differences between
    <a href="/guides/cold-frame-vs-low-tunnel/">
      cold frames and low tunnels
    </a>
    so you can choose the right setup.
  </p>

  <h3>4) Microclimate selection is critical</h3>
  <p>
    South-facing walls, windbreaks, and well-drained soil can significantly improve performance.
    In extreme northern climates, even small increases in warmth and shelter compound over time.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If your site behaves differently than regional data suggests,
    <a href="/guides/how-microclimates-change-frost-dates/">
      this guide explains how microclimates alter frost timing
    </a>.
  </p>

  <h3>How to use your numbers</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Use frost dates to define your outer boundaries.</li>
    <li>Prioritize very short-maturity and cold-tolerant crops.</li>
    <li>Assume protection is required for most warm-season plants.</li>
  </ol>

  <p class="small muted" style="margin:0.5rem 0 0 0;">
    In Nunavut, gardening success depends on crop choice, microclimate design,
    and maximizing the brief summer window.
  </p>
</section>